Lester Holt was completely biased towards Hillary. This is not an excuse, it's a fact. Claiming that a light was in fact green when you go through an intersection and get into a wreck is not a excuse, especially if you have a dash cam. Fortunately, the debate had video evidence as well.

1. Holt began by making it seem like the economy is doing extremely well right now. This is a lie. People have less high-paying jobs. Fewer adults are working. Obama has spent almost as much as every other president combined. Search CNN's article "Why doesn't 4.9% unemployment feel great"

2. Holt asked why Trump has made remarks about Rosie O'Donnell and called the girl from the beauty pageant "Miss Piggy". How dare a beauty pageant contestant be judged by her looks? It also turns out that this girl was an ex pornstar, has threatened to kill a judge, and may have been the getaway driver in an attempted murder. But what does any of this have to do with "achieving prosperity", "the direction in which America is headed", or "national security"?

3. Going into the "the direction in which America is headed" section, we immediately jump to race, and then the birther issue, insinuating that it was based on racism. Why didn't Obama release his birth certificate immediately? Isn't that more suspicious than him being black? Holt then debated Trump, something he never did with Clinton. Again, is there nothing better to mention in the allotted time concerning "the direction in which America is headed"? Maybe Socialism? The UN's agenda, change in role, or rise in power? The effects of our monumental debt?

4. Trump's taxes under Obama's tax plan. The vast majority of the extremely wealthy find numerous ways around taxes. Trump did not create this tax plan. And again he debated Trump. There are more important issues for our country than Trump's taxes.

5. The Iraq war. Hillary VOTED in support of the Iraq war. Trump has half heartedly said he may support the war. He has said maybe we shouldn't have been there in the first place. He has also said that he thinks the economy is a bigger issue currently. He has also stated that he is against the Iraq war. Search on YouTube "Donald Trump - The Iraq war (2003)" by user "Patriotic Populist". And this was BEFORE he was a politician. Again, Holt debated Trump instead of moderating.

6. The law suit on racial discrimination. Numerous people were sued in this matter, which took place a long time ago. The suit fell out and Trump was not found guilty. Again, there are more important issues to discuss during a presidential debate.

7. Holt briefly asked Hillary to comment on get emails, an issue in which she had a prepared answer which downplayed the severity of her actions and the measures she took to cover them up. He did not debate Hillary and moved on.

8. Holt brought up Trump's quote that Hillary "didn't have the presidential look". Where does this fall under "achieving prosperity", "the direction in which America is headed", or "national security"? Could our nation be facing issues more important than this?

9. Holt did not debate Hillary or interrupt her at any point. He refused to bring up the Clinton Foundation's finances, Clinton flip flopping on the Iraq war and gay marriage, Haiti, or Benghazi. And again, the email issue, for which she had prepared a great line to downplay it, he kept very brief.

Before you defend any of Hillary's mistakes, remember that is not the point of this. The point is that Lester Holt was indeed biased, which is a disgrace. Everyone has a right to a fair trial, and this is much more important than almost any court case. I personally feel that being this biased is morally bad, and bad for America. How could anyone see this as fair? Calling the claims of bias an "excuse" is an excuse in itself.

SERIOUS QUESTION ABOUT TRUMP: First off let me just say that I am NOT by any means in support of Hillary. After all it's because of people like her and her husband that we have the whole mess with NAFTA where all of our jobs can and are being shipped overseas. As bad as that is, my question has more to do with something that was proposed by Trump, and specifically that was also proposed and implemented by Bush and was a very big contributor to the 2008 great recession, by the way. If you haven't already guessed, it happens to be the tax breaks that Trump proposed tonight for the wealthiest Americans, which he himself claimed will (ALLEGEDLY) enable and/or encourage wealthy executives to create and keep jobs in this country as opposed to shipping them overseas. However, there is a giant loophole in this proposal, one which every republican since Clinton has apparently failed to acknowledge (keeping in mind that NAFTA didn't exist prior to Clinton, and so the outsourcing jobs thing would for the most part not have been an issue). At any rate, they are overlooking the fact that, as with Bush, the companies/wealthy executives/CEOs have had zero accountability to create jobs in this country in lieu of the tax breaks. Basically, it's as if they can take the tax breaks and then still continue to ship jobs overseas on top of it without any law or anything legal put in place to stop them. What's ironic is I'm seeing two sides of the same coin here. One lying possibly sociopathic side and one con man coked up side, but that's irrelevant. I mean in terms of policy.

For example, Trump's right, it is vitally important to stop outsourcing and minimize it as much as possible. Clearly it's decimating our economy and our manufacturing capabilities, which are critical in a time of crisis (ie military buildup during WW2...who do you think made all those tanks and planes for us? the Chinese?) or to help repair our crumbling infrastructure.

Likewise, the domestic industry we do have should be geared largely towards clean energy devices and products (what if Exxon or Chevy made a hybrid car that wasn't a Prius?), and working towards making America more self sufficient. Also, this revitalized industrial sector can be used to push America towards space supremacy (not asking Russia for rides in their rockets, building satellites and weapons platforms so we can cut down on conventional military spending and use that money elsewhere, and extracting rare earth elements like silicone tungsten aluminum and gold from throughout our solar system, which are rare on earth but vastly abundant elsewhere, and will make advanced technology such as green energy sources, cell phones and computers, and the rockets we use to get into space far cheaper than they are now, due to us having more raw material and an industrial sector to make them with).
To do all this we need people (the vast majority of the country actually) who think it's important enough to be worth doing and directly benefits them. Meaning Hillary is right in that regard, our primary focus should be on the working and middle class, as well as the poor and motivating them to work and work hard (though I think rich CEO's should be taxed less tbh. Not regulated less but taxed less. They should be kept in America with incentives to stay, and plenty of red tape and hassle for those who do try to outsource, but in general they'll be spending more than enough of their money already).

I could go on for a while, but the way I see it, despite both of them being crooked pieces of crap, I think both of their ideas, at least in certain respects, have some degree of merit. If we were to somehow synthesize them, then imo we could move this country forward at a much faster rate than either of these two clowns could on their own. And that's called....compromise. Two highly publicized events in America have taken place recently, well, one not so
recently. Both events, for letâ€™s say convenience sake, coincidentally went down
at night. The first event am talking about was the fight between eight-division
world champion Manny Pacquiao and five division world champion Floyd Mayweather junior in May last year (Poole, 2011).
However, it did not live up to that kind of hype. It was also billed to be the fight of the century or battle for greatness (Wikipedia, 2016).

The second event went down yester night. It was the first of the three presidential
debates in America scheduled for this year. This is the event that has gotten
me wondering whether America really has lost its grip as the superpower of the
world, literally in several sectors where we expect top talent to coalesce. My
pocket dictionary tells me that a superpower is a very powerful and influential
nation (used especially with reference to the US and the former Soviet Union
when these were perceived as the two most powerful nations in the world). Underline the part it says â€˜when these were perceivedâ€¦â€™

Mayweather, an American by all definitions, gave a what was not a very entertaining fight, much was expected from him. Pundits and other sports enthusiasts across the globe agreed to that. We wished Tyson would come back and give us a great fight, but he would not.

Come to this second event. Hillary Clinton, despite claiming that she had prepared
for the debate, did not give a spectacular performance too. Trump came through strong, articulating his issues just as we would love them to be articulated. Hillary started to hit below the belt unnecessarily towards the end of the debate and in doing so she spun what was a good debate into a mockery of a debate, a circus. This was exacerbated by a moderator who did not tame the candidates. Like a rookie pilot, Lester Holt did not control the flight of the debate (Hargrave, 2016).

Why should Americans care about the birth place of Obama as if that will stop the
shootings in the streets? Such an issue is a sideshow and it is not fit for that platform, it was trivializing the debate. Clinton was good in terms of wasting time. In football, if you waste time you get punished for it. In boxing, if you hit below the belt, you get punished too. This was a debate, and the commission for presidential debates in America should have rules governing matters time wastage.

ninety minutes to present and prosecute their case. Hillary knows she has some wrongs on her side, but like the proverbial thief that shouts â€˜thiefâ€™ she knows how to
fool media and endear herself that way to them. Her smile was not genuine
either, Trump did not see that bluff. It seems that was a strategy, they say
politics is a dirty game, the players must be dirty indeed, and some are
completely immersed in the pigsty of it.

In politics, it seems it is he or she who can mortgage the country upscale, those
of the â€˜it wasnâ€™t me mantraâ€™. Trump came through as an outsider, not because he did not have content, but because he did not come expecting the dirty game of trivial sideshows.

My take on the debate (wall-o-text inbound). TLDR: Of the 8 topics, Trump won 3 topics and Hilary won 5 of them. Hilary
won this overall because Trump couldn't stop saying stupid things.

Tax increase/decrease:
Trump won this hands down. He was agressive and hit Clinton at every turn. He came off as a bit disruptive and got punished for it a few times, but overall his rhetoric combined with his strong pressure was enough for him to put Clinton on the defensive. He managed to really pressure Clinton on her support of horrible trade deals and she became visibly flustered. This was simply an easy win.

Tax returns:
Clinton won this one. Trump got shut down when his assertions about his wealth and charities were exposed as untrustworthy. Going after Clinton's emails was a very good line of attack, but ultimately didn't help because Clinton went after it right away by correctly calling it a bait-and-switch. He then got clobbered and Trump was left to try and recover from his smeared financial image, but found no good answer. The killer line was the reversal when she said that the country was a mess because Trump didn't pay his taxes.

Race relations:
More than Clinton winning, I feel like Trump lost. His statements were confusing and self-defeating. His idea of improving race relations is by helping police? Are you kidding me? And he supports using stop-and-frisk; a policy known to have been used in a discriminatory fashion that is very unpopular with African Americans and Latin people. Trump, are you even trying? Can it be more clear that you don't give a shit? Hilary could've said literally said nothing and still won this. Clinton gave an excellent answers though. So good that even Trump shut up at this point and tried to incorporate some parts of her answers. And again a killer line from Hilary about her being prepared for this debate and prepared to be president.

Birther issue:
Given the fact that he spread the birther rumor, Trump couldn't do anything but lose here. You could pit him against a 5 year old and he would lose on this issue. Kind of a biased question but it fits in the topic of race relations I guess.

Cyber Security:
Good defense from Trump at first, but then when it came to the substance of cyber security Trump shows that he was unprepared. Trump's take home message was "We have to get very, very tough on cyber (wtf is that) and cyber warfare." I heard no real plan and I really want to know who this Cyber guy is and why we have to be so tough on him. I heard no real plans from Clinton either but at least I heard some collaborations, which means that she knows a little bit about this (I hope). Clinton just barely won this.

Home grown terrorism:
Shut up about Iraq, Trump. We're talking about home grown terrorism and how you're going to prevent it. Oh goddammit, Clinton, don't respond to Trump. Just answer the question. Anyway, I think Trump succesfully countered Clinton's answer and vice versa, but Trump was more aggressive and assertive. However, lol about Trump supporting the Iraq war. We have video evidence about this, you supported the war Trump. This round would've gone to Trump if it wasn't for the fact that he kept going on and on about how he didn't support the Iraq war (even though he totally did) and when he hung himself by saying that he has a better temperament than Clinton (even the audience lol'ed). Cllinton was all smiles after that self-inflicted injury from Trump and gained a new line of attack. Goes to Clinton because Trump killed himself.

Nuclear policies:
Trump wins because of the weak-sauce standard politician answer from Hilary. Also, Trump is right, the US can't be policeman of the world.

Clinton's presidential look:
This is a biased question if I've ever seen one. Hilary gets no points for trying to paint Trump as a sexist. Great reversal on Trump's assertion about Clinton's stamina though. Great line of attack on Hilary having bad experience. Think that Trump won this.
